related_questions.question: Why would a cardiologist order a cardiac catheterization?
related_questions.snippet: The purpose of cardiac catheterization is to find problems with how your heart is working and its blood flow. Sometimes, during a heart cath, a provider may use other procedures to fix issues. For example, they could fix a heart issue you were born with or replace your heart valve without doing open-heart surgery.

text_blocks.snippet: A heart catheterization, also known as cardiac catheterization, can reveal various heart conditions, including narrowed or blocked arteries, valve problems, and issues with heart muscle function. It allows doctors to visualize the heart and blood vessels, measure pressures within the heart, and assess blood flow. This information helps diagnose and guide treatment for various heart conditions.
snippet_highlighted_words: various heart conditions, including narrowed or blocked arteries, valve problems, and issues with heart muscle function

list.title: Coronary Artery Disease (CAD):
list.snippet: Catheterization can identify narrowed or blocked coronary arteries, which can lead to chest pain or heart attack.

list.title: Heart Valve Issues:
list.snippet: It can reveal problems with the heart valves, such as narrowing (stenosis) or leaking (regurgitation), affecting blood flow.

list.title: Heart Muscle Function:
list.snippet: The procedure can assess how well the heart muscle pumps blood, identifying issues like cardiomyopathy or heart failure.

list.title: Congenital Heart Defects:
list.snippet: It can help diagnose birth defects in the heart, such as holes between chambers.

list.title: Blood Flow:
list.snippet: The procedure can visualize blood flow through the heart and vessels, identifying blockages or abnormalities.

list.title: Pressure Measurements:
list.snippet: Catheterization allows doctors to measure blood pressure in different heart chambers and vessels, helping to assess heart function.

list.title: Oxygen Levels:
list.snippet: It can measure oxygen levels in the blood within the heart and lungs, providing insights into heart and lung function.

list.title: Angioplasty and Stenting:
list.snippet: If narrowed arteries are found, angioplasty (using a balloon to open the artery) and stenting (placing a small tube to keep the artery open) can be performed during the same procedure.

list.title: Valve Repair or Replacement:
list.snippet: In cases of severe valve problems, catheterization can help determine if valve repair or replacement is necessary.

list.title: Medication Management:
list.snippet: The information obtained from catheterization can help guide medication management for various heart conditions.
